ria Express]], [[Iberia Regional]], [[Ryanair]], [[Vueling]]\n|-\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|Switzerland}} [[Switzerland]]\n| 170.139\n| {{decrease}} 6.83%\n| [[easyJet Switzerland]], [[Swiss]], [[Vueling]]\n|-\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[United Kingdom]]\n| 138.756\n| {{increase}} 22.5%\n| [[easyJet]], [[Ryanair]]\n|-\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Italy]]\n| 92.269\n| {{decrease}} 7.89%\n| [[Ryanair]], [[Vueling]]\n|-\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Germany]]\n| 86.532\n| {{decrease}} 15.43%\n| [[Lufthansa]], [[Ryanair]]\n|-\n| 6\n| {{flagicon|Ireland}} [[Ireland]]\n| 55.049\n| {{increase}} 25.04%\n| [[Aer Lingus]]\n|-\n| 7\n| {{flagicon|France}} [[France]]\n| 54.499\n| {{increase}} 1.2%\n| [[Vueling]]\n|-\n| 8\n| {{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Netherlands]]\n| 28.907\n| {{increase}} 0.6%\n| [[Vueling]]\n|-\n| 9\n| {{flagicon|Belgium}} [[Belgium]]\n| 17.996\n| {{increase}} 6.82%\n| [[Vueling]]\n|-\n| 10\n| {{flagicon|Malta}} [[Malta]]\n| 5.986\n| {{-}} -\n| [[Ryanair]]\n|}\n<br>\n{|class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse\"\n|- bgcolor=red\n|+ '''Busiest Carriers at Santiago de Compostela Airport (2019)<ref name=\"Estad\u00edsticas aena-aeropuertos\"/>\n\n|-\n! Rank\n! Carriers\n! Passengers\n! % Change<br>2018 / 19\n|-\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|Ireland}} [[Ryanair]]\n| 1.239.243\n| {{increase}} 11.61%\n|-\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Vueling]]\n| 682.463\n| {{increase}} 13.21%\n|-\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Iberia Express]]\n| 481.184\n| {{increase}} 7.3%\n|-\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|Switzerland}} [[easyJet Switzerland]]\n| 134.972\n| {{decrease}} 5.65%\n|-\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Air Europa]]\n| 100.428\n| {{decrease}} 7.04%\n|-\n| 6\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Iberia Regional]]\n| 64.941\n| {{decrease}} 23.08%\n|-\n| 7\n| {{flagicon|Ireland}} [[Aer Lingus]]\n| 54.700\n| {{increase}} 24.87%\n|-\n| 8\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Lufthansa]]\n| 49.523\n| {{decrease}} 15.19%\n|-\n| 9\n| {{flagicon|Austria}}{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[easyJet]]\n| 40.240\n| {{decrease}} 26.15%\n|-\n| 10\n| {{flagicon|Switzerland}} [[Swiss International Air Lines]]\n| 17.763\n| {{decrease}} 26.29%\n|}\n\n== Ground transportation ==\n\n===Road===\nThe airport is linked with [[Santiago de Compostela]] (13&nbsp;km) by the [[Autov\u00eda A-54]]. This motorway is currently being extended to [[Lugo]] (94.5&nbsp;km) where it will connect with the [[Autov\u00eda A-6]], providing toll-free motorway access to the rest of Spain; and to the French border through the [[Autov\u00eda A-8]] that intersects with the [[Autov\u00eda A-6]] near [[Lugo]]. Nearby [[Autopista AP-9]] connects the airport directly to [[A Coru\u00f1a]] (66&nbsp;km), [[Ferrol, Galicia|Ferrol]] (88&nbsp;km), [[Pontevedra]] (75&nbsp;km), [[Vigo]] (100&nbsp;km) and the Portuguese border. [[Ourense]] (116&nbsp;km) is reachable through the [[Autopista AP-53]] that connects with the [[Autopista AP-9]].\n\nThere are several major car rental companies at the airport. The airport has more than 5,000 short and long-term covered parking spaces in the new terminal building. In addition, there are several low-cost, long-term private parking facilities around the airport.\n\n===Bus services===\nA city bus service operated by Empresa Freire every 30 minutes connects the airport with the center of Santiago de Compostela, and the bus and train terminals in the city. From the station in Santiago de Compostela, private coach operators run direct services in a multiple daily basis to most cities and towns in Galicia, including [[A Coru\u00f1a]], [[Ferrol, Galicia|Ferrol]], [[Lugo]], [[Ourense]], [[Pontevedra]] and [[Vigo]], as well as long-distance services to the rest of Spain, and international services. In addition, three regional services link the airport directly to [[A Coru\u00f1a]], to [[Lugo]], including several stops in the [[French Way]] of the [[Camino de Santiago]], and to the [[:es:La Mari\u00f1a|A Mari\u00f1a]] coastal area (home to [[As Catedrais beach]]) in the province of [[Province of Lugo|Lugo]].\n\n===Rail===\nThere are no rail facilities at the airport. However the [http://www.adif.es/en_US/infraestructuras/estaciones/31400/informacion_000050.shtml train station in Santiago de Compostela], located 12&nbsp;km. away, is connected to the airport by the city bus service every 30 minutes. There are combined available train+bus tickets to and from the airport. The train station in Santiago de Compostela has medium and long-distance high-speed [[Alvia]] and [[AVE]] services to most cities in Galicia, including [[A Coru\u00f1a]], [[Ferrol, Galicia|Ferrol]], [[Ourense]], [[Pontevedra]], [[Vilagarc\u00eda]] and [[Vigo]]; and further to [[Madrid Chamart\u00edn railway station|Madrid Chamart\u00edn]] and the rest of [[Spain]].\n\n===Foot and bike===\nThe [[Camino de Santiago]] runs next to the runway of the airport. This is the busiest and final journey in the [[Camino de Santiago]] that goes through the famous [[Monte do Gozo]]. There are dedicated pathways for both pedestrians and bikers towards the city. The walking distance from the runway to the [[Santiago de Compostela Cathedral|Cathedral]] is estimated at 10.90&nbsp;km.\n\n==Accidents and Incidents==\n*On 3 March 1978, a [[Douglas DC-8|McDonnell Douglas DC-8-63]] operated by [[Iberia LAE|Iberia]] from [[Madrid\u2013Barajas Airport]] with 211 passengers and 11 crew members, registration EC-BMX. The aircraft touched down far down the runway after a high approach, aquaplaned off the runway, dropped into a hollow 20m deep and caught fire. The crash was settled with 70 injured people, 10 of them seriously injured, and no fatalities.<ref>http://www.aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19780303-0</ref>\n*On 7 June 2001, a [[Beechcraft Super King Air|Beechcraft B300C Super King Air 350]], registration F-GOAE, departed from Le Mans-Arnage Airport (LME), France, to Santiago De Compostela Airport (SCQ), Spain, on a cargo flight according to instrument flight rules. Near the destination airport, the meteorological conditions were reported to be good, and the crew requested a visual approach to runway 17, even though the active runway was 35. Once cleared to land, the aircraft encountered a fog patch and from this moment it began a high ate descent (2000 to 3000&nbsp;ft/min). A minute after entering an unexpected and unforeseen fog patch, the aircraft struck some trees in level flight and with an airspeed of 148 kt. The wings and engines detached from the fuselage, and they dragged along a scrubland area until they came to a stop. The crew suffered minor injuries and the aircraft was completely destroyed.<ref>http://www.aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20010607-0</ref>\n*On 2 August 2012, an Airnor [[Cessna 500|Cessna 500 Citation I]], registration EC-IBA, flying from [[Asturias Airport|Asturias]] crashed whilst on approach to the airport with the loss of both crew members.<ref>[http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20120802-0 Santiago de Compostela accident]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n* [http://www.aena.es/es/aeropuerto-santiago/index.html Official website]\n\n{{Portalbar|Spain|Aviation}}\n{{Airports in Spain}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Santiago de Compostela]]\n[[Category:Airports in Galicia (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Santiago de Compostela]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1935]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox airport\n| name                = Santiago - Rosal\u00eda de Castro Airport\n| nativename          = {{small|''Aeroporto de Santiago - Rosal\u00eda de Castro''<br>Aeropuerto de Santiago - Rosal\u00eda de Castro}}\n| nativename-a        = \n| nativename-r        = \n| image               = Aena_Santiago.svg\n| image-width         = 300\n| image2               = Santiago_de_Compostela_-_LEST_Terminal.jpg\n| image2-width         = 300| WMO                 = 8041\n| IATA                = SCQ\n| ICAO                = LEST\n| type                = Public/Military\n| owner               = [[ENAIRE]]\n| operator            = Aena\n| city-served         = [[Santiago de Compostela|Santiago]], [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], [[Spain]]\n| location            = [[Santiago de Compostela]]\n| focus_city          = {{ubl| [[Ryanair]]| [[Vueling]]}}\n| built               = 1932\n| metric-elev         = \n| elevation-m         = 370\n| elevation-f         = 1213\n| coordinates         = {{Coord|42|53|47|N|08|24|55|W|type:airport_region:ES-GA|display=inline,title}}\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.aena-aeropuertos.es/santiago/en}}\n| image_map           = \n| image_map_caption   = \n| pushpin_map         = Spain Galicia#Spain\n| pushpin_label       = '''SCQ'''\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Galicia\n| r1-number           = 17/35\n| r1-length-m         = 3,200\n| r1-length-f         = 10,499\n| r1-surface          = [[Asphalt]]\n| stat-year           = 2019\n| stat1-header        = Passengers\n| stat1-data          = 2,903,427\n| stat2-header        = Passengers change 18-19\n| stat2-data          = {{increase}}6.5%\n| stat3-header        = Aircraft movements\n| stat3-data          = 22,396\n| stat4-header        = Movements change 18-19\n| stat4-data          = {{increase}}2.5%\n}}\n[[File:Aeropuerto de Lavacolla - 01 - Torre de control.jpg|thumb|Control tower]]\n\n'''Santiago\u2013Rosal\u00eda de Castro Airport''' ({{lang-gl|Aeroporto de Santiago-Rosal\u00eda de Castro}}, {{lang-es|Aeropuerto de Santiago-Rosal\u00eda de Castro}}) {{airport codes|SCQ|LEST}}, previously named ''Lavacolla Airport'' and also known as '''Santiago de Compostela Airport''', is an [[international airport]] serving the [[Autonomous communities of Spain|autonomous community]] and [[1833 territorial division of Spain|historical region]] of [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] in [[Spain]]. It is the [[List of the busiest airports in Spain|2nd busiest airport]] in [[Green Spain|northern Spain]] after [[Bilbao Airport]]. It has been named after the [[Galicia (Spain)|Galician]] [[Romanticism|romanticist]] writer and [[poetess]], [[Rosal\u00eda de Castro]], since 12 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dea\u00f1o Santiago |first1=Carlos |title=Rebautizo oficial del aeropuerto como Rosal\u00eda de Castro |url=https://www.elcorreogallego.es/santiago/ecg/rebautizo-oficial-aeropuerto-rosalia-castro/idEdicion-2020-03-12/idNoticia-1235142/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |publisher=El Correo Gallego |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe airport is located in the parish of Lavacolla, 12&nbsp;km from [[Santiago de Compostela]] and handled 2,903,427 passengers in 2019. It is the main [[focus city]] of [[Vueling]] in the northwest [[Iberian Peninsula]], and [[Ryanair]]'s only [[focus city]] in [[Green Spain|Northern Spain]]. The [[Christian pilgrimage]] route of the [[Camino de Santiago]] runs near the airport.\n\n==History==\nThe airport was set up by a group of aviation enthusiasts in October 1932 and two months directors were chosen to select where the airport was going to be built. In 1935 construction work started at the airport where two years later on 27 September 1937 the first scheduled flight from Santiago de Compostela took place. {{Citation needed|date=March 2016}} After the Spanish Civil war, political prisoners (who were held in the concentration camp of Lavacolla) were forced to work in the construction of the airport.<ref>http://www.laopinioncoruna.es/galicia/2010/03/13/miles-presos-construyeron-obras-civiles-militares-galicia-1960/366159.html</ref>\n\nIn 1969 a new terminal was built at the airport. It has had several expansions taking place since it opened.{{Citation needed|date=March 2016}} It closed in 2011 following a brand new terminal being built at the airport. In 1981, a cargo terminal was built, giving the airport capacity to handle cargo flights.<ref>[http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20120802-0 History of Santiago de Compostela Airport]</ref> During the 1990s, the airport had non-stop service to [[South America]] operated by [[Viasa]].<ref>http://airline-memorabilia.blogspot.com/2011/08/viasa-1995-espana.html</ref>\n\nOn 13 October 2011 a new passenger terminal opened at the airport, replacing the old terminal, opened in 1969 and remodeled in 1993.\n\n==Terminal==\nThe airport currently has one operating terminal.  The old terminal at Santiago de Compostela airport opened in 1969 and had lots of expansions during its lifetime. The old terminal closed on the night of 13 October 2011 when operations transferred to the new terminal.\n\nThe new terminal at Santiago de Compostela Airport officially opened on 13 October 2011 and passenger operations transferred there the following day. It is adjacent to the old terminal and has a size of 74,000&nbsp;sq m. It has 22 check-in desks, 3 security checkpoints, 4 baggage carousels, and 13 gates of which 5 have airbridges. The baggage hall is split into two zones, one for [[Schengen Area|Schengen]] flights and one for Non-Schengen. It can handle as many as 4 million passengers per year.<ref>[http://www.aena-aeropuertos.es/csee/Satellite/NATSantiago/en/Page/1237551007362//New-terminal.html New Terminal]</ref> The terminal is due to be expanded in the future. This includes adding another 5 airbridges to 5 of the current gates as well as 3 more baggage carousels and an expanded shopping area.<ref>[http://www.aena-aeropuertos.es/csee/Satellite/NATSantiago/en/Page/1237551228358/1237551007352/The-airport-in-figures.html New Terminal Expansion]</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n{{Airport-dest-list\n<!-- -->\n| [[Aer Lingus]] | [[Dublin Airport|Dublin]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Air Europa]] | [[Gran Canaria Airport|Gran Canaria]] <br>'''Seasonal:''' [[Fuerteventura Airport|Fuerteventura]], [[Ibiza Airport|Ibiza]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Air Europa adds new Ibiza routes in 1H20 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/287836/air-europa-adds-new-ibiza-routes-in-1h20/ |website=Routesonline |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref> [[Lanzarote Airport|Lanzarote]], [[Menorca Airport|Menorca]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Air Europa expands Mahon network in 1Q20 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/287901/air-europa-expands-mahon-network-in-1q20/ |website=Routesonline |accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref> [[Palma de Mallorca Airport|Palma de Mallorca]], [[Tenerife North Airport|Tenerife\u2013North]], [[Tenerife South Airport|Tenerife\u2013South]] \n<!-- -->\n| [[easyJet]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Gatwick Airport|London\u2013Gatwick]]\n<!-- -->\n| {{nowrap|[[easyJet Switzerland]]}}| [[EuroAirport Basel-Mulhouse-Freiburg|Basel/Mulhouse]], [[Geneva International Airport|Geneva]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Edelweiss Air]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Zurich Airport|Zurich]] (begins 4 July 2020)<ref>https://reisetopia.ch/news/edelweiss-santiago-de-compostela/</ref>  \n<!-- -->\n| [[Iberia Express]] | [[Adolfo Su\u00e1rez Madrid\u2013Barajas Airport|Madrid]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Iberia Regional]] | [[Bilbao Airport|Bilbao]], [[Tenerife North Airport|Tenerife\u2013North]] <br>'''Seasonal:''' [[Cristiano Ronaldo International Airport|Funchal]], [[Gran Canaria Airport|Gran Canaria]], [[Menorca Airport|Menorca]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Lauda (airline)|Lauda]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Palma de Mallorca Airport|Palma de Mallorca]] (begins 1 June 2020) <ref>{{cite web |last1=Santamar\u00eda |first1=Ux\u00edo |title=Operar\u00e1 en Lavacolla la antigua aerol\u00ednea del piloto Niki Lauda  |url=https://www.elcorreogallego.es/santiago/ecg/operara-lavacolla-antigua-aerolinea-piloto-niki-lauda/idEdicion-2020-02-25/idNoticia-1232114|website=El Correo Gallego |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n<!-- -->\n| [[Lufthansa]] | [[Frankfurt Airport|Frankfurt]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Ryanair]] | [[Alicante Airport|Alicante]], [[Barcelona\u2013El Prat Airport|Barcelona]],  [[Orio al Serio Airport|Bergamo]], [[Gran Canaria Airport|Gran Canaria]], [[Lanzarote Airport|Lanzarote]], [